<br>
I am very sorry for your loss.  <br>
<br>
There is very good advice in this thread.  My addition would be this:  saddness, mourning, feelings of loss and even depression are in most cases normal human emotions and should not be ignored.  Coming to grips with why you are feeling a certain way, rather than hiding from or trying to bury the emotions, is the healthiest means of dealing with them.<br>
<br>
Losing a close family member is often times the most trying period in one's life, and everyone needs to find their own means of healing.  But talking about it with people who share the loss or have gone through similar experiences, remembering the person, and giving yourself adequate time to mourn in the true sense are excellent cobblestones with which to pave yourself back to happiness.  If you have a religious faith, then explore that as well, as a large part of religion deals with the transition from material life to the afterlife.<br>
<br>
Best wishes,<br>
