<br>
There is noone on this Earth that can possibly feel or completely understand how you must be feeling right now, but Im sure I speak for everyone when I say we are thinking of you.<br>
 Its important for you to do whatever you feel you need to. Everybody deals with grief in a different way. Some people cope by withdrawing, others by returning to work. The important thing to remember is that its going to hurt like hell for a time, but that it does get better. As cliched as it is, time is a great healer.<br>
<br>
Not only have I lost 2 grandmothers, and a close friend to suicide, I have been a psychiatric nurse for over 8 years.<br>
I've spent significant time with people who have lost loved ones, and Ive had a fair bit of training in the field of grief and loss.<br>
<br>
Remember that there are fantastic people out there who work in the field of Grief and Loss (numbers probably in your phone book, or numbers available through your local hospital/community health centre) that are always available to talk to if you don't feel you are coping, or if you simply want someone else to talk to.<br>
<br>
It will take time, but you will get through this difficult time.<br>
<br>
