<br>
Allow yourself to grieve, Laney.  I'm not saying wallow in the sadness, but just acknowledge how you feel and don't try to push it away.  The grief will have to be dealt with sooner or later, and I've found it's easier to deal with it sooner.  You'll never forget your Mom, Laney, and I can tell you from experience that even 13 years later, you'll hear or see something that reminds you of her, and you'll still have those moments of sadness.  But it does get easier over time.  <br>
<br>
My sister and I have spent a lot of time over the years remembering the good times with Daddy, and that has been a particular comfort for both of us.  It helps to be able to share those memories.  Sometimes, when someone dies, people are afraid of causing you more grief, and so they steer conversations away from the topic of the person who is gone.  Don't let that keep you from expressing yourself.  Find someone you can share all of that with.<br>
<br>
You've already made a good start on moving on in resuming your normal activities.  That helps a lot.  There is comfort sometimes in sameness and routine, and it can help pull you out of the sadness when it threatens to overwhelm.<br>
<br>
The other last bit of advice I'll give you is to ignore people who think you should take anti-depressants to &quot;help you cope&quot;.  I don't know if you've gotten that or if you will.  When we put my Mom in hospice care recently and I was really grieving, I had several people suggest that.  I'm glad that I didn't do it, though.  It's one thing if you truly fall into a deep depression, but not if all you are doing is normal grieving.  Allow yourself to have those feelings, and be able to move on in your life, remembering her and her love for you.<br>
<br>
 <p>Maritzia Soulhealer<br>
30th Season Cleric of Rodcet Nife<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uellywig.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ellywig</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 960<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/5/02 3:53:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=588.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: When loved ones die.</span><hr size=1> Time will take the wounds down to a bearable, transient ache. It never completely stops hurting, but it becomes bittersweet, instead of merely painful, to be reminded.<br>
<br>
The price of love is the inevitable risk that someday there will be a void in our lives in the shape of that lost love. But it is a far emptier life to never love anything, so it is a price most of us have to pay, someday.<br>
<br>
Grieve as best suits you - and don't be afraid to comfort yourself along the way. If praline cheesecake or classic horror movies or old issues of MAD magazine or listening to the same N'Sync song 83 times in a row make the ache go away for a while, stock up and indulge as needed. Don't rush stuff that you don't have to do right away... if you need to tend to something, do. But don't sort old scrapbooks or something just because it ought to get done - many things pack up nicely and wait well. If you have a close friend or two, see if you can lean a bit on them for loose ends. Sometimes the small stuff is overwhelming for a bit.<br>
