<br>
And, while I am still petrified of that day, when I fear my world will end, I heard something the other day on some HBO thing, and it gave me more peace than I knew was possible. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Love is stronger than death.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I dont know your religious background, or if you have a particular faith in anything... but have faith in love, if nothing else. You love your mother, and while not on this plane, she loves you. And that will always connect you, soul to soul. <br>
<br>
If you want to talk to her, then talk to her. If you want to scream and yell at her, do it. If you want to hug her, close your eyes and remember how it felt to do so. She may or may not hear you... but thats really not the point. The point is to get the words and the pain out of you. I personally hold the opinion that she WILL hear you, and she will hug you back. <br>
<br>
I dont know how I feel about the idea of holding off the pain for a time until it becomes softer... probably because i am a very emotional person, and it would take a strength of will i do not possess to keep the grief away. I have found something that helps me. It might be a little crazy, a little unorthodox... but regardless, it helps me...<br>
<br>
Feel the pain. Feel the sadness. Feel the grief. Feel it as utterly and wholly as you can. Let it flow through your entire body and mind, until it surrounds you. Then, take a step outside of yourself, and notice how it feels. Dont think to yourself &quot;i miss her&quot; ... pay attention to how your physical body feels, what parts of you ache, what parts of you burn, what parts of you throb. Feel the areas of your soul that are weakend in her absence. Feel the part of your mind that is heavy. <br>
Once I fully understand exactly how it FEELS to be so sad, I can acknowledge that I felt/feel it, and can be done with it for a little while. Then later, when I want to or need to feel it again, I can with a better understanding of it. And I notice that after the first time, I can sense the pain ebb slightly. Maybe my throat doesnt burn so much, or my arms arent so heavy. So I know its getting &quot;better&quot;. <br>
<br>
Another added &quot;benefit&quot; of doing this, is you'll realize when you pay such scruity to the weakness of yourself, you'll be to see with glaring clarity the parts of you that are strong. Its like turning the contrast on your monitor to high. The whites are almost blinding, and the blacks are deep and intense. And once you get to know yourself that way, you will quickly find those strengths when you feel the weakness pulling on you.<br>
<br>
I am truely sorry for your loss. I wish for you the strength to get through it. <p><font color = FF3333>
